description.value: Terracotta figure of Bes: the lower section of the figure has been broken and reattached, and there is some surface damage at the back of the crack. There are traces of white and pink paint on the left ear, and green paint on the base and the plumes of the crown. The terracotta was moulded in separate halves; the back, as with many Ptolemaic and Roman terracottas, is shaped but unmodelled. This terracotta figure represents the Egyptian deity Bes. The dwarf god stands naked, with his hands resting on his thighs. He wears a leonine mask with a snub nose, stylized manelike beard and furrowed brow; his tongue is stuck out. The paws of the lion-skin cape are visible on his shoulders and around his neck is an amulet in the form of an animal head. On his head Bes wears his usual plumed  crown,  but  one  of the   feathers  is moulded and the others are plain: details may have been added with paint.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of Harpokrates, riding a goose. A youthful figure, probably Harpokrates, astride a goose which walks forward to the right over rocky ground. The rider holds the goose round the neck and is naked except for a himation draped over his left shoulder and falling both in front and behind him. The back is plain, with a circular vent. Both the head of Harpokrates and of the goose are broken away, the rider’s shoulder and arm are damaged, and the vent and the base have pieces missing. Hollow, from two-piece mould. Orange-brown Nile silt with a thick light-grey core and abundant fine gold mica and rare white inclusions. The surface has fired brown over much of the object.
